Tools/PPCLoad <ELFProgram>

loads and executes an ELF Program. It works like
a shell start of M68k programs. So if the ELF program
can run standalone and doesn`t need a special interface
it may work this way.

@EndNode


@Node "US_TOOLS" "PowerUP.guide/US_TOOLS"
@Next "DE_HARDWARE"
@Prev "US_RUN"
@Toc "Main"

The AmigaOS PPC Tools are in the directory <Tools/>

 o PPCLoad <Name>
   a simple PPC Elf program loader for PPC programs
   which work without incoming data.

 o PPCLoadTimer <Name>
   a simple PPC Elf program loader for PPC programs
   which work without incoming data.
   It calculates how long a PPCRunObject() takes which
   creates a synchron task.

 o PPCInfos
   a program which shows informations about the CPU type.

 o PPCShowTasks
   a program which shows informations about all PPC tasks.

 o PPCSignalTask ID/K,Name,Signal/N,SignalMask/K
   a program which sends a PPC Task a signal.
   The name of the task has to be written in the correct way or
   you can pass the TaskID if the Taskname occurs several times.
   With SignalMask you can send several Signals by a SignalMask
   long word.
   (Like AmigaOS c:break)

 o PPCDebug
   the PPC Debugger. Learning by using is the goal here:-)

 o SetDebugSpeed
   small tool to change the amiga`s serial output speed. Helpful
   if you think 9600 Baud is too slow.

@EndNode






@Node "DE_HARDWARE" "PowerUP.guide/DE_HARDWARE"
@Next "DE_CACHES"
@Prev "US_TOOLS"
@Toc "Main"

 o CyberStorm MK2 PPC603p addon board.

   This board has a 32bit ram bus due to the MK2`s 32bit ram bus so
   the ram performance isn`t very high.

 o CyberStormPPC 060/PPC604p board.

   This board has a 64bit memory bus with the following timings.

   70ns SIMMs
   M68k 32BIT Write takes 5-2-2-2 (50Mhz busclock)
   M68k 32BIT  Read takes 5-2-2-2 (50Mhz busclock)
   PPC  64BIT Write takes 5-3-3-3 (66Mhz busclock)
   PPC  64BIT Write takes 5-3-3-3 (66Mhz busclock)

   60ns SIMMs
   M68k 32BIT Write takes 5-1-1-1 (50Mhz busclock)
   M68k 32BIT  Read takes 5-1-1-1 (50Mhz busclock)
   PPC  64BIT Write takes 5-2-2-2 (66Mhz busclock)
   PPC  64BIT Write takes 5-2-2-2 (66Mhz busclock)

@EndNode

@Node "DE_CACHES" "PowerUP.guide/DE_CACHES"
@Next "DE_API"
@Prev "DE_HARDWARE"
@Toc "Main"


 What is a CPU Cache ?

 A CPU Cache is a method to get data faster to the cpu which is
 accessed the most. A Cache is used where it`s too expensive to
 use a fast memory system or where it`s impossible to speed up an
 external memory interface to the speed of an internal CPU cache.

 How does a modern CPU Cache work ?

 A modern cache is like a small database with the setsize of a
 CPU Burst. A set is called cache line with a 4 Access Burst
 means for the 68060 a cache line size of 16 Bytes(32Bit Memory Bus)
 and for the PPC603/604 a cache line size of 32 Bytes(64Bit Memory Bus).

 The cache would look like this:

 8KB Cache = 512 Cache lines with 16 Bytes.

Line MemoryAddress   CacheLineNumber   Contents 0 - 3rd LONGWORD            Status

0:    $1000             $100           aaaaaaaa bbbbbbbb cccccccc dddddddd  LOADED
                                                                            (Not changed by the CPU)

1:    $21234530         $2123453       eeeeeeee ffffffff gggggggg hhhhhhhh  DIRTY
                                                                            (changed by the CPU)

511:  ---------         --------       ???????? ???????? ???????? ????????  EMPTY

 This is a nice method to speed up your accesses to normal memory but
 not everything in a computer is normal random access memory. There
 are also a lot I/O memory addresses.
 The cache system above wouldn`t work for I/O addresses because the contents
 of the I/O space isn`t controlled by the CPU so the CPU doesn`t know if
 something changed there. Another reason the cache system above doesn`t work
 for I/O space is that you can`t load or write a cache line from I/O space
 because you may touch non existing memory or you read/write has a different
 meaning for IO Addresses.
 Therefore there are several cache modes and these cache modes are normally
 controlled by the MMU which controlls the memspace in pages(Normally 4K).
 So for each memory page you can set different cache modes which are
 explained below:

 o No Cache
   the cache is off, so a READ and WRITE go directly to
   the memory. But the cpu buscontroller can still optimize
   the writes. It could optimize 4 close writes into a
   Burst write by reordering the 4 writes into a line for example.
   The writes/reads aren`t in precise mode.

 o No Cache Serialized
   the cache is off, so a READ and WRITE go directly to
   the memory and the accesses have to go out in precide order.
   I/O space is mapped that way. For example the custom chipset area.


 o Writethrough
   the cache is active for reads but writes go directly to the memory.
   So the memory and cache contents are always the same.
   The cache is refilled in line bursts which are 16 Bytes on the 68060
   and 32 Bytes on the PowerPC.

 o Copyback
   the cache is active for reads and writes. Cache Lines are read and
   written in 16 Bytes bursts for the 68060 and 32Bytes for the PowerPC.
   A cacheline can be dirty. This means data in that line was modified
   and hasn`t been written back to memory yet.
   So if you write something to an address which line hasn`t been loaded
   to the cache yet the following happens.
   If no empty cacheline is found an used line has to be replaced by
   the cache line. If this used cache line is dirty it is first written
   back to memory to update the memory with the current state.
   Now the new cacheline is loaded and then the write operation changes
   the data in the new cacheline while the Memory still contains the old
   value.
   Now imagine what happens if another device(DMA,CPU) accesses the
   memory which lines are in the cache of the cpu.
   Yes..the contents of the cache isn`t valid anymore but the processor
   has no idea that certain cache lines aren`t valid anymore and goes on
   using it.
   The consequence is data corruption.

 o The PPC has some additional modes that controll its cache protocoll.
   The cache protocoll "MESI" is used to keep data valid between
   several PPCs in an SMP system where memory is shared between processors.
   (SMP=Symetrical Multi Processing)

 o Current OS mechanism to avoid data corruption during DMA

   o Chipram is generally marked as "cache inhibited", so the blitter
     can change the data without the cpu keeping corrupt data
     in the cache.

   o GfxBoard Memory is marked as "cache inhibited serialized"
     by the 68040 and 68060.library because it`s no used memory.
     Therefore it is no problem if the gfxboard blitter changes data.
     The Phase5 680xx libraries mark known gfxboard`s framebuffers
     as nonserialized because a precise access order isn`t necessary
     which only slows down the cpu.

   o CachePreDMA() and CachePostDMA()
     CachePreDMA() clears the cache and then marks the mmu
     pages(4K) to "no cache" for the cache size. It also does
     provide a nesting for pages if 2 CachePreDMA() share
     a page.
     After a transfer CachePostDMA tries to set back CopyBack
     for that area but that depends on the nesting.
     The design of CachePreDMA() was also to provide a virtual
     memory system but that couldn`t work because of a serious
     design fault.
     (Device reentrance problem which would lead too far to
      describe here)
     Another problem you can`t avoid with CachePreDMA() is that
     it has to mark pages as Not Cacheable that are only used by
     1 Byte of the transfered area so all the code or data which
     is only in that page takes a serious performance penality.

   o The tricky version
     1) CacheFlush
     2) If DMA-READ(SCSI-WRITE), do normal DMA
     3) If DMA-WRITE(SCSI-READ), do the following steps

       o Check the Address and calculate the Bytes you have to
         transfer without DMA into that memory area to reach the
         next cacheline.

       * poll these Bytes(maximal 15 Bytes) or DMA these into
         the chipram and copy them back into the real destination.

       o then start the real DMA(only in size of cache lines)

       o check if there`s still something to transfer and repeat the *)
         method.

         Why is it that difficult ?
         Look at this example:

         0) Directly after the CacheFlush

            Cache Line Offset    Cache Line Contents   Memory    Comment

            0                    --------              aaaaaaaa  not in the cache because of cacheflush
            4                    --------              bbbbbbbb  not in the cache because of cacheflush
            8                    --------              cccccccc  DMA start address
            12                   --------              dddddddd  DMA area

         1) After the CacheFlush but before the DMA start..some other Task touched the cache line.
            Maybe by going through the Memlist or whatever.

            Cache Line Offset    Cache Line Contents   Memory    Comment

            0                    aaaaaaaa              aaaaaaaa  Loaded because of the other Task
            4                    bbbbbbbb              bbbbbbbb  Loaded because of the other Task
            8                    cccccccc              cccccccc  Loaded because of the other Task(DMA start address)
            12                   dddddddd              dddddddd  Loaded because of the other Task(DMA area)

         2) Start DMA
            Cache Line Offset    Cache Line Contents   Memory    Comment

            0                    aaaaaaaa              aaaaaaaa  Loaded because of the other Task
            4                    bbbbbbbb              bbbbbbbb  Loaded because of the other Task
            8                    cccccccc              ????????  changed by the DMA in memory
            12                   dddddddd              ????????  changed by the DMA in memory

         3) Now you see that the line in the cache is invalid and if the data at offset 0 and 4 is
            changed by the other task you get even a dirty cache line which is written back sometime later
            and we would get this.

            Cache Line Offset    Cache Line Contents   Memory    Comment

            0                    xxxxxxxx              xxxxxxxx  Changed by the other Task
            4                    yyyyyyyy              yyyyyyyy  Changed by the other Task
            8                    cccccccc              cccccccc  Memory corrupt..dma image invalid
            12                   dddddddd              cccccccc  Memory corrupt..dma image invalid

 After you understand the basic issues of the cache problem let`s
 see how all this looks with the PowerUP board where the problem
 is even worse.
 Instead of 1 copyback CPU(68060) and a nocache DMA unit we have 2
 copyback CPUs so the problem is on both sides.
 Both CPUs have a CopyBack cache which means that both processors load
 cache lines into their caches, manipulate the data indepently and only
 write back the lines when needed.
 So now we have the problem that both processors don`t know about
 the data the other processor changes and this can cause data
 corruption if you`re not careful.
 The easier way is to better avoid sharing memory between both
 CPUs to avoid such problems.
 If that isn`t possible the ppc.library has to cacheflush on the
 PPC and on the 060 after an operation.
 Another problem here is that if you use memory with the PPC the
 PPC reads/writes this memory with his 32 byte cache lines and
 the 68060 has only a 16byte cache line. So if both cache lines
 share the same memory you may get data corruption after a writeback.
 Therefore the ppc.library offers a Memory API for the ppc which
 fixes at least the cache line problems.
 This API allocates memory in 32byte aligned spaces instead of the
 default 8 byte alignment that the exec memory routines use.
 Let`s discuss this problem with the example of the PPC AmigaOS
 interface.

 0) Internally the PPC has to tell the 68060 to execute
    an AmigaOS function and give back the result to the PPC
    program.
    For normal/static parameters the ppc.library is using
    a noncacheable memory area where it stores parameters and
    results so the processor has to reload the data each time
    it wants it reads it.
    A very important law is that the PPC MUST NOT change a
    structure the 68060 controlls.
    Let`s go into detail.

 1) A PPC program which does the following:

      PPCClose(File);

    has to pass the static parameter File to the 68060 so
    it can call PPCClose() with the parameter File.
    This is a rather easy case. The PPC isn`t allowed to
    read/write the memory which File points to.
    So normally this call wouldn`t need any cacheflush on
    both cpus.

 2) A PPC program which does the following:

      PPCOpen(FileName,MODE);

    On first look this call looks like PPCClose(File) but there
    is an important difference. The static parameter Filename
    points to a memory which is in the cache of the PPC and
    this memory is used by the PPCOpen() call on the 68060.
    So here we need a cacheflush by the PPC before the 68060
    is notified about the new job and then the M68k needs a
    cacheflush after the operations is done so the FileName
    memory is removed from the cache. Because the M68k doesn`t
    change the Filename cache lines in the cache a cacheflush
    doesn`t write back this line so it`s safe to use stack/static
    memory on the PPC side for the FileName array.

 3) A PPC program which does the following:

      PPCRead(File,Buffer,Size);

    Here the M68k changes the Buffer the PPC controlls. This
    needs a CacheFlush on the PPC and then afterwards on the
    M68k to get a valid Buffer.
    You MUST use PPCAllocMem on the PPC to allocate Buffer otherwise
    you may get cache line problems.


 4) The final rule is that you aren`t allowed to shared memory
    between PPC tasks which is used by the M68k bridge.
    This means that you must be VERY careful in situations like
    this.

    struct TaskAFrame
    {
      ULONG	Semaphore;	/* shared between Task A and B */
      char	Buffer[256];	/* Filename Buffer */
    }

    PPCOpen(TaskAFrame->FileName,MODE);

    because of the cacheline problems this may cause a lot problems
    so you better allocate M68k bridge memory by PPCAllocMem()
    to avoid sharing the same cache lines with different PPC tasks.

 PS. People which think the 060 snooping and PPC MESI protocol would
     solve these problems should take a look at the 68060 snooping mode
     which makes it impossible to have a valid shared copyback cache
     for both cpus.

@EndNode

@Node "DE_ABI" "PowerUP.guide/DE_ABI"
@Next "DE_ADE"
@Prev "DE_CACHES"
@Toc "Main"

The word ABI means Architecture Binary Interface and it defines
the meaning of the usermode register usage so there`s a standard
for all compilers and for calling functions.

Small example with the AmigaOS M68k ABI:

A0..A1	volatile
A2..A5  saved
A6      saved, used as the Library Base Ptr in OS Calls
A7      stack pointer
D0..D1  volatile
D2..D6  saved
ccr     volatile

to give something you can compare the following informations with.
The real new thing to the M68k is the usage of the stack.

1) There`s only some general register used with the meaning of
   the stack.
2) Under the AmigaOS M68k ABI the stack was simply used like a FILO
   where you put arguments after another on the stack in some linear
   way. The PPC caller stackframe works completely different to
   optimize memory accesses. The include stdarg.h should give you
   more understandable informations how "..." stack parameters are
   accessed (first stored in registers, afterwards on the stack)


The ABI PowerUP uses is the System V.4 ABI which is used by
GCC, Linux PPC, NetBSD and probably a lot more PPC systems.


   The System V.4 ABI stack frame looks like:

	SP---->	+---------------------------------------+
		| back chain to caller			| 0
		+---------------------------------------+
		| saved LR				| 4
		+---------------------------------------+
		| Parameter save area (P)		| 8
		+---------------------------------------+
		| Alloca space (A)			| 8+P
		+---------------------------------------+
		| Local variable space (L)		| 8+P+A
		+---------------------------------------+
		| saved CR (C)				| 8+P+A+L
		+---------------------------------------+
		| Save area for GP registers (G)	| 8+P+A+L+C
		+---------------------------------------+
		| Save area for FP registers (F)	| 8+P+A+L+C+G
		+---------------------------------------+
	old SP->| back chain to caller's caller		|
		+---------------------------------------+

   The registers are used as follows (volatile means that a function does not
have to preserve its value when it returns, saved means that a function must
restore its value before returnning):

    r0		volatile, may be used by function linkage
    r1		stack pointer
    r2		reserved for system
    r3	.. r4	volatile, pass 1st - 2nd int args, return 1st - 2nd ints
    r5  .. r10	volatile, pass 3rd - 8th int args
    r11	.. r12	volatile, may be used by function linkage
    r13		small data area pointer
    r14 .. r31	saved
    f0		volatile
    f1		volatile, pass 1st float arg, return 1st float
    f2  .. f8	volatile, pass 2nd - 8th float args
    f9  .. f13	volatile
    f14 .. f30	saved
    f31		saved, static chain if needed.
    lr		volatile, return address
    ctr		volatile
    xer		volatile
    fpscr	volatile*
    cr0		volatile
    cr1		volatile**
    cr2 .. cr4	saved
    cr5 .. cr7	volatile

* The VE, OE, UE, ZE, XE, NI, and RN (rounding mode) bits of the FPSCR may be
changed only by a called function such as fpsetround that has the documented
effect of changing them, the rest of the FPSCR is volatile.

** Bit 6 of the CR (CR1 floating point invalid exception bit) is set to 1 if a
variable argument function is passed floating point arguments in registers.

   When alloca is executed, the back chain to the caller's stack frame and the
link register save area must be updated.

   The parameter save area does not contain space to store the 8 integer
arguments.  If it is desired that they be stored, the callee must allocate
space to save it in the local variable area of the stack.  Structures and
unions are copied into temporary slots and an address of the temporary slot is
passed as the argument.

   Variable argument functions must store the registers used for passing
arguments that aren't used for fixed arguments into a 96 word area on the stack
in the local variable section.  If bit 6 of the CR is not 1, it doesn't have to
save the floating point registers.  The va_list type is defined as follows:

	typedef struct {
	    char gpr;			/* index to next saved gp register */
	    char fpr;			/* index to next saved fp register */
	    char *overflow_arg_area;	/* ptr to next overflow argument */
	    char *reg_save_area;	/* ptr to reg save area */
	} va_list[1];




@EndNode

@Node "DE_ADE" "PowerUP.guide/DE_ADE"
@Next "DE_GCC"
@Prev "DE_API"
@Toc "Main"

The compiler we use to compile PowerUP programs is the PowerPC GCC crosscompiler
you can find in the ADE distribution which is maintained by Fred Fish.
The GEEK Gadgets CD(produced by Fred Fish) contains the whole ADE enviroment with
the M68k and PPC compiler.
The following files and directories are important for PowerUP programmers.

bin/
    ppc-amigaos-ar

     The PPC GNU link lib creator
     (=ppc-amigaos-ranlib)

    ppc-amigaos-as

     The PPC GNU assembler
     (=ppc-amigaos-gas)

    ppc-amigaos-c++

     The PPC GNU C++ compiler frontend which starts the compiler,assembler and linker
     (=ppc-amigaos-g++)

    ppc-amigaos-c++filt

     The PPC GNU C++ symbols decoder

    ppc-amigaos-g++

     The PPC GNU C++ compiler frontend which starts the compiler,assembler and linker
     (=ppc-amigaos-c++)

    ppc-amigaos-gas

     The PPC GNU assembler
     (=ppc-amigaos-as)

    ppc-amigaos-gasp

     The PPC GNU macroassembler frontend

    ppc-amigaos-gcc

     The PPC GNU C compiler frontend which starts the compiler,assembler and linker

    ppc-amigaos-ld

     The PPC GNU linker

    ppc-amigaos-nm
    ppc-amigaos-objcopy

     The PPC GNU ELF->xyz object format converter

    ppc-amigaos-objdump

     The PPC GNU ELF object viewer which shows the contents of an object.
     (Disassembler,Data,symbols,relocs,sections,...)

    ppc-amigaos-ranlib

     The PPC GNU link lib creator
     (=ppc-amigaos-ar)

    ppc-amigaos-size

     The PPC GNU object section size viewer

    ppc-amigaos-strings

     The PPC GNU object context sensitive string search program

    ppc-amigaos-strip

     The PPC GNU object file cleanup program which deletes all unnecessary informations
     from the object file.

guide/
    All kinds of Amiga Guide formated GNU documentation.

man/
    All GNU information in man format.
    (man -c gcc)


ppc-amigaos/
    bin/
    include/
     The PPC PowerUP system includes are supposed to be here when a basic
     ANSI stdio link lib exists.

    lib/
     The PPC PowerUP link libraries are supposed to be here.


@EndNode


@Node "DE_GCC" "PowerUP.guide/DE_GCC"
@Next "DE_GCCPROBLEMS"
@Prev "DE_ADE"
@Toc "Main"

How to compile file.c to powerpc assembler ?

 o ppc-amigaos-gcc -O3 -S -v -o file.s file.c
   @{"C Source" Link "DE_GCC_C"}

How to link file.o to file.elf ?

 o ppc-amigaos-gas -o file.o file.c

ppc-amigaos-ld -r file.o -o file.elf
   @{"ASM Source" Link "DE_GCC_ASM"}

-r IS A MUST. It tells the linker to generate relocatable code.
But it has also an important disadvantage that it doesn`t output
errors when the file.elf has still unresolved references.
(This problem on one of my lists to be fixed for ADE)

How can i take a look at the file.c contents ?

ppc-amigaos-objdump --section-headers --all-headers --reloc --disassemble-all --syms --line-numbers file.elf
   @{"ObjDump" Link "DE_GCC_OBJ"}

If you look for *UND* symbol entries you see that the file hasn`t been linked
correctly.

@EndNode

@Node "DE_GCCPROBLEMS" "PowerUP.guide/DE_GCCPROBLEMS"
@Next "DE_GCC_C"
@Prev "DE_GCC"
@Toc "Main"

GCC PPC doesn`t have the same structure alignment rules like the Amiga M68k
compilers which leads to incompatible structures.

!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ATTENTION !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
!                                                                   !
! o You MUST be careful with alignment of Bytes used in SAS         !
!   and on the PPC. The GCC does a long alignment for a long        !
!   instead of a word alignment                                     !
!   Example:                                                        !
!                                                                   !
!     SAS            GCC                                            !
!   0  ln_Succ   0 ln_Succ                                          !
!   4  ln_Pred   4 ln_Pred                                          !
!   8  ln_Type   8 ln_Type                                          !
!   9  ln_Pri    9 ln_Pri                                           !
!   10 ln_Name   12 ln_Name                                         !
!   the ln_Name Entry because before that there ln_Pri/ln_Type      !
!   Bytes.                                                          !
!                                                                   !
!   This is a serious problem. And we plan to fix this with         !
!   a GCC enhancement                                               !
!                                                                   !
! o You MUST be careful with alignment of DOUBLE floats used in SAS !
!   and on the PPC. The PPC needs an alignment of LONG for DOUBLE.  !
!   SAS only aligns on word border so it`s your business to add     !
!   pad words if necessary.                                         !
!                                                                   !
!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ATTENTION !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

Temporary solution to this problem:

struct Node
{
	struct Node	*ln_Succ;
	struct Node	*ln_Pred;
	UBYTE		ln_Type;
	UBYTE		ln_Pri;
	char		*ln_Name __attribute((packed));  /* Word alignment */
} __attribute((packed)); /* Word alignment */

struct List
{
	struct Node	*lh_Head;
	struct Node	*lh_Tail;
	struct Node	*lh_TailPred;
	UBYTE		lh_Type;
	UBYTE		lh_pad __attribute((packed)); /* Word alignment */
}__attribute((packed)); /* Word alignment */

@EndNode

@Node "DE_GCC_C" "PowerUP.guide/DE_GCC_C"
@Next "DE_GCC_ASM"
@Prev "DE_GCCPROBLEMS"
@Toc "Main"

;/*
delete hello.s 
ppc-amigaos-gcc -Iinclude: -O2 -S hello.c
delete hello.o
ppc-amigaos-gas  hello.s -o hello.o
ppc-amigaos-ld -r hello.o -o hello
ppc-amigaos-objdump --section-headers --full-contents --all-headers --disassemble-all hello >hello.dump
quit
*/

#define ANZ 200

int array[ANZ];

int value=0x12345678;


int main(void)
{
int i;

  for (;;)
  {
    for (i = 0 ; i < 200 ; i++)
    {
      array[i] = value;
    }
  }
  return(0x11223344);
}

@EndNode

@Node "DE_GCC_ASM" "PowerUP.guide/DE_GCC_ASM"
