@Node "DE_POWERUPAPI" "PowerUP.guide/DE_POWERUPAPI"
@Next "OT_UPD"
@Prev "DE_GCC"
@Toc "Main"

The ppc.library controlls the communication between M68k and
the PowerUP board.
On the M68k side it`s a normal amiga library which offers an
API for loading PPC Elf objects, creating PPC Tasks, PPC Memory
allocation to avoid @{"Cache Line" Link "DE_CACHES"} problems,
PPC Exception handling(PPC Enforcer) and very important the
communication to the PPC.

To run a PPC Task you have to load the PPC program somehow into
the system memory. The PPC program itself must provide relocation
informations and resolve informations so the loader can built up
a correct image of the PPC Program.
We chose ELF as the PPC object format standard because it`s the
most used and supported object format in the world. It supports
runtime linking, relocations, shared libraries, custom sections
and so on.

A PPC program image in memory is created by PPCLoadObject() which
returns a Handle called ElfObject. This handle is needed to start
a PPC Task or to get symbol, reloc and section informations about
the ELF itself.
All loaded ELFObjects are inserted into an internal database to
support an automatic @{"Segtracker" Link MO_SEGTRACKER} like feature.
When PPCCreateTask() is called with the ElfObject it creates the
PPCTask`s AmigaOS M68k message task in which context all PowerUP`s
AmigaOS functions run.
For example if a PPCTask demands memory the memory allocation
works inside this message task.
The name of the Msg Task is "PPC:MsgHandler "+TaskName which is
normally the name of the ElfObject.

On the PowerPC side runs a small Multitasking kernel that
keeps controll over the PPC Tasks, PPC IPC, memory management
and communication to the M68k side.
It also offers some little support functions like protected and
not protected list management functions based on the AmigaOS
list functions.
How the PowerUP kernel can be accessed is NOT defined anywhere
and can change randomly to avoid any problems when the PowerUP
API is ported to another OS.
So you simply call your PowerUP functions like extern functions
in C or assembler. The ppc.library`s Elf Loader resolves these
symbols and creates the code so the Elf program can call PowerUP
Kernel functions.

***Currently*** the PowerUP kernel functions linked with the ELF
program are internal System Call stubs, if it`s a real System Call
or direct link to the function, if it`s a simple support function like strlen().
Example:

;bl=Branch with link register(Return Address) register is the usual
;way to call external functions
	bl	ExternalFunction
;The ELF Loader now sees a not resolved function and replaces this
;with
	bla	AbsoluteAddress
;where ba=Branch Absolut with link register(Return Address)


The PowerUP Task Scheduler uses the normal Amiga Round Robin system
and it depends on the AmigaOS VBlank interrupt like the Exec Scheduler,
so if you disable() that interrupt the PowerPC still runs but can`t
switch a task. The ppc.library`s VBlank Inthandler simply interrupts
the PPC to do a schedule.
There`s no significant speed difference to the PPC using the internal
timer.

The M68k ppc.library API is decribed in @{"ppc.doc" Link /autodocs/ppc.doc/main}.
The PPC API is decribed in @{"powerup.doc" Link /autodocs/powerup.doc/main}.

The needed includes can be found in:

 o powerup/clib
    The ppcdiss.library protos
    @{"powerup/clib/ppcdiss_protos.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppcdiss_protos.h/main}
    The ppc.library protos
    @{"powerup/clib/ppc_protos.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppc_protos.h/main}

 o powerup/gcclib
    The PPC Kernel protos
    @{"powerup/gcclib/powerup_protos.h" Link /include/powerup/gcclib/powerup_protos.h/main}

 o powerup/lvo
    The AmigaOS library LVOs. Useful for own PPCCallOS usage.

 o powerup/ppcdisslib
    The PPCDiss library includes
    @{"powerup/ppcdisslib/ppcdiss.h" Link /include/powerup/ppcdisslib/ppcdiss.h/main}

 o powerup/ppclib
    Global ppc.library and lowlevel includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/ppc.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/ppc.h/main}

    AmigaOS - PPC function interface includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/interface.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/interface.h/main}

    AmigaOS - PPC message interface includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/message.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/message.h/main}

    PowerUP memory system includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/memory.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/memory.h/main}

    PowerUP Task includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/tasks.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/tasks.h/main}

    PowerUP Semaphore includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/semaphore.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/semaphore.h/main}

    PowerUP ELF interface includes
    @{"powerup/PPCLib/object.h" Link /include/powerup/PPCLib/object.h/main}

 o powerup/pragmas
    The ppcdiss.library pragma
    @{"powerup/pragmas/ppcdiss_pragmas.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppcdiss_pragmas.h/main}
    The ppc.library pragma
    @{"powerup/pragmas/ppc_pragmas.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppc_pragmas.h/main}

 o powerup/proto
    The ppcdiss.library proto
    @{"powerup/proto/ppcdiss.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppcdiss.h/main}
    The ppc.library proto
    @{"powerup/proto/ppc.h" Link /include/powerup/clib/ppc.h/main}

 o powerup/ppcinline
    The GCC PPC AmigaOS Inlines

 o powerup/ppcpragmas
    The SAS/GCC C PPC AmigaOS Pragmas

 o powerup/ppcproto
    The SAS/GCC PPC AmigaOS proto


@EndNode

@Node "DE_FD2INLINE" "PowerUP.guide/DE_FD2INLINE"
@Next "DE_M68kPPC_0"
@Prev "DE_POWERUPAPI_1"
@Toc "Main"

fd2inline converts Amiga FD and proto files into a
CallOS libstub. The default CacheMode is IF_CACHEFLUSHALL
so there`s a possibility to optimize a call to your
needs.

@EndNode


@Node "DE_M68kPPC_0" "PowerUP.guide/DE_M68kPPC_0"
@Next "OT_UPD"
@Prev "DE_FD2INLINE"
@Toc "Main"

To pass argument parameters from M68k to the PPC in a PPCCreateTask
call use the following Tags from @{"PowerUP/PPCLib/tasks.h" Link /include/PowerUP/PPCLib/tasks.h/main}

o PPCTASKTAG_ARG1,Arg1
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG2,Arg2
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG3,Arg3
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG4,Arg4
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG5,Arg5
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG6,Arg6
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG7,Arg7
o PPCTASKTAG_ARG8,Arg8

and on the PPC Side

int	Start(Arg1,Arg2,Arg3,Arg4,Arg5,Arg6,Arg7,Arg8)

@EndNode


